// ---- utmctl: cli-help probes. Each is about what PARSES. Where a flag's BEHAVIOUR is at stake the
// claim names its doc-contains refutation, per the G5 trap.
{"id": "utmctl-file-help-admits-guest-agent", "kind": "cli-help", "file": "specs/macos-ci/05-utm-automation.md", "argv": ["utmctl", "file", "--help"], "expect": "Guest agent file operations", "claim": "utmctl's own help text calls `file` a GUEST AGENT operation -- the clearest self-admission of the 05 s2.2 gate. Unlike utmctl-help-lists-exec this probe is not merely `the verb parses`: the parser itself names the missing dependency. The refutation of any hope that it works on a macOS guest is utmctl-exec-needs-qemu-guest-agent."}
{"id": "utmctl-usb-help-lists-connect", "kind": "cli-help", "file": "specs/macos-ci/05-utm-automation.md", "argv": ["utmctl", "usb", "--help"], "expect": "connect", "claim": "TRAP, twin of utmctl-start-help-lists-disposable: `utmctl usb` advertises list/connect/disconnect on every host, including one that can only run Apple-backend macOS guests. A subcommand in --help proves it parses, not that it works. The refutation is utmctl-usb-is-qemu-only."}
{"id": "utmctl-start-help-lists-recovery", "kind": "cli-help", "file": "specs/macos-ci/05-utm-automation.md", "argv": ["utmctl", "start", "--help"], "expect": "--recovery", "claim": "`utmctl start --recovery` parses. Unlike its sibling --disposable, this flag DOES work for an Apple-backend macOS guest (macOS 13+): see utm-recovery-mode-disables-sip. The pair is the point -- --help cannot tell you which of two adjacent flags is real."}
{"id": "utmctl-delete-help-says-no-confirmation", "kind": "cli-help", "file": "specs/macos-ci/05-utm-automation.md", "argv": ["utmctl", "delete", "--help"], "expect": "there is no confirmation", "claim": "utmctl delete's own help text states there is no confirmation, corroborating 05 s2.1's `No confirmation dialog -- irreversible` for the AppleScript `delete` verb it wraps."}
{"id": "utmctl-attach-help-has-index", "kind": "cli-help", "file": "specs/macos-ci/05-utm-automation.md", "argv": ["utmctl", "attach", "--help"], "expect": "--index", "claim": "`utmctl attach [--index N]` selects among serial devices. attach reads the HOST end of a ptty and needs no guest agent, which is why 05 s4.2's working set is `lifecycle plus host-side serial` rather than lifecycle-only."}

