// L6 confirmed by execution, and refined. `git grep -c` prints `path:count`; the merged weak control
// expects only ":", which git's own `fatal: cannot change to '<path>': ...` also satisfies.
{"id": "xaudit-09-git-grep-fatal-line-contains-a-colon", "kind": "cli-help", "file": "specs/macos-ci/09-dotfiles-under-test.md", "argv": ["git", "-C", "/Users/bossjones/dev/bossjones/NO-SUCH-REPO-utm-probe", "grep", "-c", "stdinIsATTY"], "expect": ":", "claim": "L6, CONFIRMED BY EXECUTION not by reading: against a nonexistent repo `git grep -c` emits `fatal: cannot change to '<path>': No such file or directory`, which contains `:`. So CONTROL-git-grep-c-emits-colon-when-present (expect `:`) PASSES against a repo that does not exist and proves nothing about `path:count`. Ledger's CONTROL-git-grep-emits-real-path-count-token (expect `home/.chezmoi.yaml.tmpl:`) is the correct fix. REFINEMENT: the pair is nonetheless jointly sound -- in that same broken world the two must_fail negatives BOTH fail loudly, because the fatal line also contains `:`. The weak control degrades DIAGNOSIS, not DETECTION; the suite can never go silently green."}
